<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-sequences" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Sequences</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sequences-definitions">
    <title>Definitions</title>

    <p>
      In this book, an <term>infinite
      sequence</term><idx><h>sequence</h><h>infinite</h></idx> is a
      function whose domain has the same order type as <m>(\N, \le)</m>.
      Since we will only consider infinite sequences here, we simply call
      them <term>sequences</term>. We often regard real numbers as constant
      sequences.
    </p>

    <p>
      If <m>x</m> is a sequence, we write <m>x_n</m> for its value at
      <m>n\in\N</m> and call <m>x_n</m> the <term><m>n</m>-th
      term</term><idx><h>term</h><h>of a sequence</h></idx> of the sequence.
      We denote the sequence by <m>(x_n)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Since a real sequence is just a function <m>\N\to\R</m>,
      notions such as <term>bounded above</term>, <term>bounded
      below</term>, <term>bounded</term>, <term>increasing</term>, and
      <term>decreasing</term> apply exactly as they do for functions. An
      increasing (resp. a decreasing) sequence is bounded below (resp. above)
      by its first term. A sequence is <term>constant</term> if and only
      if it is both increasing and decreasing. We say that <m>(x_n)</m> is
      <term>strictly increasing</term> if <m>x_m \lt x_n</m> whenever <m>m
      \lt n</m>. The concept <term>strictly decreasing</term> is defined
      similarly.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-basic-sequences">
      <statement>
        <ul>
          <li><m>(1/n)</m> is decreasing and bounded.</li>
          <li><m>(n)</m> is increasing and bounded below, but not bounded above.</li>
          <li><m>((-1)^n)</m> is bounded, but neither increasing nor decreasing.</li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      A real sequence <m>(x_n)</m> is called <term>null</term><idx>null
      sequence</idx> if for every <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m> there exists
      <m>N\in\N</m> such that <me>|x_n|&lt;\varepsilon \quad\text{for all }
      n\ge N.</me>
    </p>

    <p>
      Equivalently, <m>(x_n)</m> is null if for every <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>,
      the inequality <m>|x_n|&lt;\varepsilon</m> holds for all but finitely
      many <m>n</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-one-over-n-null">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The sequence <m>(1/n)</m> is null.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      We say that a sequence <m>(x_n)</m> <term>converges</term><idx>convergent
      sequence</idx> to <m>L\in\R</m>, written <m>x_n\to L</m> or
      <m>\lim_n x_n = L</m>, if the sequence <m>(x_n-L)</m> is null. In that
      case <m>L</m> is called a <term>limit</term><idx>limit of a
      sequence</idx> of the sequence. A sequence is <term>convergent</term>
      <idx>convergent sequence</idx> if it has a limit. A sequence is
      <term>divergent</term><idx>divergent sequence</idx> if it does not
      converge.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sequences-fundamental-results">
    <title>Fundamental Results</title>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-null-sequence-basic-operations">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>(x_n)</m> and <m>(y_n)</m> be real sequences.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p><m>(x_n)</m> is null if and only if <m>(-x_n)</m> is null if
          and only if <m>(|x_n|)</m> is null.</p></li>
          <li><p>If <m>(x_n)</m> is null and <m>(y_n)</m> is bounded, then
          <m>(x_ny_n)</m> is null.</p></li>
          <li><p>If <m>(x_n)</m> and <m>(y_n)</m> are null, then
          <m>(x_n+y_n)</m> is null.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
        <p>
          For (1), note that <m>|-x_n|=|x_n|</m>, so the three conditions
          are equivalent.
        </p>

        <p>
          For (2), choose <m>B \gt 0</m> with <m>|y_n|\le B</m> for all
          <m>n</m>. For any <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, <m>|x_n| \lt
          \varepsilon</m> and hence <m>|x_n y_n| \le B|x_n| \le
          B\varepsilon</m> for all but finitely many <m>n</m>. Since
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> is arbitrary, so is <m>B\varepsilon</m>.
          This shows that the sequence <m>(x_ny_n)</m> is null.
        </p>

        <p>
          For (3), given <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>, choose <m>N_1,N_2</m>
          so that <m>|x_n|&lt;\varepsilon/2</m> for <m>n\ge N_1</m> and
          <m>|y_n|&lt;\varepsilon/2</m> for <m>n\ge N_2</m>. Then for <m>n\ge
          \max\{N_1,N_2\}</m>, the triangle inequality gives <m>|x_n+y_n|\le
          |x_n|+|y_n|&lt;\varepsilon</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-convergent-sequence-unique-limit">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A convergent sequence has a unique limit.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n\to L</m> and <m>x_n\to L'</m>. Then
          <m>(L-x_n)</m> and <m>(x_n-L')</m> are null sequences, so by
          <xref ref="prop-null-sequence-basic-operations"/> their sum
          <m>(L-L')</m> is also null.
        </p>
        <p>
          A constant sequence is null only when its constant value is zero.
          Therefore <m>L-L'=0</m>, so <m>L=L'</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-convergent-sequence-bounded">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every convergent sequence is bounded.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n\to L</m>. Then there exists <m>N\in\N</m> such that
          whenever <m>n \ge N</m>, <m>|x_n-L|&lt;1</m>, and so by the triangle
          inequality,
          <me>|x_n| \lt |x_n-L| + |L| \lt 1+|L|.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Hence <m>
            |x_n|\le B:=\max\{|x_1|,\dots,|x_N|,|L|+1\}
          </m> for every <m>n</m>, so <m>(x_n)</m> is bounded.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-monotone-convergence">
      <title>Monotone Convergence Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every bounded increasing sequence converges to the supremum of its
          set of terms, and every bounded decreasing sequence converges to
          the infimum of its set of terms.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We prove the increasing case. In this case, the set of terms
          <m>S=\{x_n:n\in\N\}</m> is bounded above and nonempty; let <m>s</m>
          be its supremum.
        </p>

        <p>
          For any <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>, <m>s-\varepsilon</m> is not an
          upper bound of <m>S</m>, so there exists <m>N</m> with
          <m>s-\varepsilon&lt;x_N</m>. Because the sequence is increasing,
          whenever <m>n \ge N</m>,
          <me>
            s-\varepsilon&lt;x_N\le x_n\le s \lt s + \varepsilon.
          </me>

          Therefore <m>|x_n-s|&lt;\varepsilon</m> for all <m>n\ge N</m>, so
          <m>x_n\to s</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          The decreasing case follows by applying the same argument to
          <m>(-x_n)</m>, or by a direct dual proof using infima.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      The next proposition shows that the usual algebraic operations on
      convergent sequences again produce convergent sequences, and that taking
      limits commutes with these operations.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-limit-laws-sequences">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>a_n\to A</m> and <m>b_n\to B</m>. Then:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p><m>a_n+b_n\to A+B</m>,</p></li>
          <li><p><m>a_nb_n\to AB</m>,</p></li>
          <li><p><m>1/a_n\to 1/A</m>, provided <m>A\ne0</m> and <m>a_n\ne0</m>
          for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Since <m>(a_n-A)</m> and <m>(b_n-B)</m> are null,
          <xref ref="prop-null-sequence-basic-operations"/> gives
          <m>(a_n+b_n-(A+B))=((a_n-A)+(b_n-B))</m> null. Hence
          <m>a_n+b_n\to A+B</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Also
          <m>
            a_nb_n-AB
            = a_n(b_n-B) + (a_n-A)B.
          </m>
          By <xref ref="prop-convergent-sequence-bounded"/>, the sequence
          <m>(a_n)</m> is bounded. Therefore <m>(a_n(b_n-B))</m> is null, and
          since the constant sequence <m>(B)</m> is bounded,
          <m>((a_n-A)B)</m> is also null.
          Their sum is null, so <m>a_nb_n\to AB</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the reciprocal, choose <m>N_0</m> such that
          <m>|a_n-A|&lt;|A|/2</m> for all <m>n\ge N_0</m>. Then for
          <m>n\ge N_0</m>,
          <m>|a_n|\ge |A|-|a_n-A|&gt;|A|/2</m>, so in particular
          <m>a_n\ne0</m>. Hence
          <m>
            \left|\frac1{a_n}-\frac1A\right|
            = \frac{|a_n-A|}{|a_n||A|}
            \le \frac{2}{|A|^2}|a_n-A|.
          </m>
          Since <m>(a_n-A)</m> is null, it follows that <m>1/a_n\to 1/A</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-squeeze-lemma">
      <title>Squeeze Lemma</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>a_n\le x_n\le b_n</m> for all <m>n\in\N</m> and
          <m>a_n\to L</m>, <m>b_n\to L</m>. Then <m>x_n\to L</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>. Since <m>a_n\to L</m> and
          <m>b_n\to L</m>, there exists <m>N</m> such that for all
          <m>n\ge N</m> we have
          <m>-\varepsilon&lt;a_n-L&lt;\varepsilon</m> and
          <m>-\varepsilon&lt;b_n-L&lt;\varepsilon</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Using <m>a_n-L\le x_n-L\le b_n-L</m>, we obtain
          <m>-\varepsilon&lt;x_n-L&lt;\varepsilon</m> for all <m>n\ge N</m>.
          Therefore <m>x_n\to L</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-sequences-approximate-sup-inf">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S\subseteq\R</m> be nonempty.
          If <m>S</m> is bounded above, then there exists an increasing
          sequence <m>(x_n)</m> in <m>S</m> such that <m>x_n\to \sup S</m>.
          If <m>S</m> is bounded below, then there exists a decreasing
          sequence <m>(y_n)</m> in <m>S</m> such that <m>y_n\to \inf S</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We prove the bounded-below case. Let <m>a=\inf S</m>. If
          <m>a\in S</m>, then the constant sequence <m>y_n=a</m> has the
          required properties.
        </p>
        <p>
          Now assume <m>a\notin S</m>. Choose <m>y_1\in S</m>. Inductively,
          suppose <m>y_k\in S</m> has been chosen. Since
          <m>a&lt;(a+y_k)/2&lt;y_k</m>, the number <m>(a+y_k)/2</m> is not a
          lower bound of <m>S</m>. Thus there exists <m>y_{k+1}\in S</m> with
          <m>a&lt;y_{k+1}&lt;(a+y_k)/2&lt;y_k</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          This constructs a decreasing sequence in <m>S</m> with
          <m>0&lt;y_{n+1}-a&lt;(y_n-a)/2</m> for all <m>n</m>. By induction,
          <m>0&lt;y_n-a\le (y_1-a)/2^{n-1}</m>. Since the right-hand side tends
          to <m>0</m>, the squeeze lemma gives <m>y_n\to a=\inf S</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The bounded-above case is proved similarly, or by applying the
          bounded-below case to <m>-S</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-limit-preserves-nonnegativity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>x_n\to L</m> and <m>x_n\ge0</m> for all <m>n</m>, then
          <m>L\ge0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose instead that <m>L&lt;0</m>. Then for every <m>n</m>,
          <m>x_n-L\ge -L=|L|</m>, so <m>|x_n-L|\ge |L|&gt;0</m>. This
          contradicts <m>x_n\to L</m>. Therefore <m>L\ge0</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-limit-preserves-order">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>x_n\to x</m>, <m>y_n\to y</m>, and <m>x_n\le y_n</m> for all
          <m>n</m>, then <m>x\le y</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          The sequence <m>(y_n-x_n)</m> converges to <m>y-x</m> by
          <xref ref="prop-limit-laws-sequences"/>, and each term is
          nonnegative. Hence <m>y-x\ge0</m> by
          <xref ref="prop-limit-preserves-nonnegativity"/>, so <m>x\le y</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-sequences-finite-changes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If two sequences differ in only finitely many terms, then they have
          the same convergence behavior. More precisely, either both diverge,
          or both converge and have the same limit.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n=y_n</m> for all <m>n\ge N_0</m>. If <m>x_n\to L</m>
          and <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>, choose <m>N\ge N_0</m> such that
          <m>|x_n-L|&lt;\varepsilon</m> for all <m>n\ge N</m>. Then
          <m>|y_n-L|=|x_n-L|&lt;\varepsilon</m> for all <m>n\ge N</m>, so
          <m>y_n\to L</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The converse is identical. Therefore the two sequences have the same
          convergence behavior.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sequences-subsequences">
    <title>Subsequences</title>

    <p>
      A <term>subsequence</term><idx>subsequence</idx> of a sequence
      <m>(x_n)</m> is a sequence of the form <m>(x_{n_k})</m>, where
      <m>(n_k)</m> is a strictly increasing sequence of natural numbers.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-subsequence-of-convergent-sequence">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every subsequence of a convergent sequence converges to the same
          limit.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n\to L</m> and <m>(x_{n_k})</m> is a subsequence.
          Since <m>(n_k)</m> is strictly increasing, we have <m>n_k\ge k</m>
          for every <m>k</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Let <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>. Choose <m>N</m> such that
          <m>|x_n-L|&lt;\varepsilon</m> for all <m>n\ge N</m>. If
          <m>k\ge N</m>, then <m>n_k\ge k\ge N</m>, so
          <m>|x_{n_k}-L|&lt;\varepsilon</m>. Hence <m>x_{n_k}\to L</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>
</section>
